      <description>Slow cooking is simple and nothing beats rummaging in your cupboards to pull together a slow cooker meal. Here is the second part of our slow cooker ingredients series, The Slow Cooker Store Cupboard. 
Corn starch or flour – These ingredients are handy for thickening and and for using when sautéing meat before adding to [...]&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.ovalslowcookers.co.uk/slow-cooker-advice-tips/slow-cooker-store-cupboard-part-2/"&gt;The Slow Cooker Store Cupboard &amp;#8211; Part 2&lt;/a&gt; is a post from: &lt;a href="http://www.ovalslowcookers.co.uk"&gt;Oval Slow Cookers&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;



Other handy slow cooker posts:&lt;ol&gt;&lt;li&gt;&lt;a href='http://www.ovalslowcookers.co.uk/best-slow-cooker-recipes/slow-cooking-making-the-perfect-chicken-stock/' rel='bookmark' title='Permanent Link: Slow Cooking: Making the Perfect Chicken Stock'&gt;Slow Cooking: Making the Perfect Chicken Stock&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/oval-slow-cookers/Oval_Slow_Cookers-The_Slow_Cooker_Store_Cupboard__Part_2.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="all you care to eat" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/60216816@N00/131116124/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" src="http://farm1.static.flickr.com/50/131116124_c191aad605_m.jpg" border="0" alt="all you care to eat" /></a>Slow cooking is simple and nothing beats rummaging in your cupboards to pull together a slow cooker meal. Here is the second part of our slow cooker ingredients series, The Slow Cooker Store Cupboard. </p>
<p><strong>Corn starch or flour</strong> – These ingredients are handy for thickening and and for using when sautéing meat before adding to the slow cooker. If you apply a light coating of flour to meat and then sauté the meat in a small amount of olive oil, this will create some little bits of fully flavored &#8220;sticky bits&#8221; which you can then add to your slow cooker. Adding cornstarch to the liquid left in the slow cooker can make tasty gravy for dishes like potatoes or rice. You can also use flour as a thickener, but cornstarch makes lump-free gravy.</p>
<p><strong>Stock</strong> – You always need liquid to start the cooking process in a slow cooker. But instead of just using water as usual, try using stock instead. Beef, chicken, and vegetable stock can be bought as cubes, liquid or powder in most supermarkets. Or you can check out my <a class="ld_link" href="http://www.ovalslowcookers.co.uk/best-slow-cooker-recipes/slow-cooking-making-the-perfect-chicken-stock/" target=" " title="chicken stock recipe">chicken stock recipe</a> for the slow cooker. Most shop-bought stock also comes seasoned already and it’s a simple way to add some flavour to your slow cooking.</p>
<p><strong>Meat </strong>– Although this article is about what&#8217;s in your storecupboard, meat is often the largest part of a (non-veggie) slow cooker meal, so make sure you have some of your favourite cuts in the home freezer. Don&#8217;t forget that tough cuts of meat will cook great and end up almost melingt in your mouth when fully cooked. This is because slow cooking adds moisture and tenderises meat that would dry out and be tough and stringy if oven cooked instead.</p>
<p>If you have these ingredients in your kitchen, you can make loads of simple slow cooker meals. If you make sure you have them always in, you’ll always have lots of ideas for dinner.</p>
