&lt;/ol&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;a type="audio/mpeg" href="http://podcasts.odiogo.com/get_mp3.mp3?f=/oval-slow-cookers/Oval_Slow_Cookers-Slow_Cooking-_Making_the_Perfect_Chicken_Stock.mp3"&gt;Click here to play&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br&gt;</description>
      <content:encoded><![CDATA[<p><a title="Door Welcome Sign by Photos8.com" href="http://www.flickr.com/photos/33538284@N03/3695683828/" target="_blank"><img class="alignleft" src="http://farm3.static.flickr.com/2575/3695683828_56aa4b1ba9_m.jpg" border="0" alt="Door Welcome Sign by Photos8.com" /></a>Slow cooking is one of the most economical ways to cook and one recipe that always reminds me of how easy a slow cooker is to use is when I make homemade chicken stock.</p>
<p>Before I had a slow cooker, making stock was a drawn out process involving lots of boiling on the stove &#8211; it used to take all day!</p>
<p>Now, my chicken stock takes just a couple of easy steps and tastes even more delicious.</p>
<p>Here&#8217;s how I do it:</p>
<p><strong>Chicken: </strong>I use the chicken carcass left over from our roast chicken dinner. After picking off any meat to be used for sandwiches the next day, I simply place the chicken into my <a class="ld_link" href="http://www.ovalslowcookers.co.uk/category/oval-slow-cookers/" target=" " title="oval slow cooker">oval slow cooker</a> (if you have a circular one you may need to squish it in a little, but that doesn&#8217;t affect the stock making process).</p>
<p><strong>Liquid:</strong> I then add water to the slow cooker til it just covers the carcass. If I have any left over gravy or vegetable cooking water then I&#8217;d add that in too.</p>
<p><strong>Vegetables:</strong> Throw in a roughly chopped onion (if you include a bit of browned skin this will give the stock a nice golden glow). Also good to add are a chopped carrot and a celery stick (you can include the leaves).</p>
<p><strong>Herbs and spices</strong>: You can add your herbs and spices according to taste. I like to add whole black peppercorns, a peeled garlic clove, a couple of bay leaves and any fresh &#8220;woody herbs&#8221; such as rosemary and thyme (you can add the stalks).</p>
<p><strong>Cooking Procedure: </strong>Simply cover the slow cooker and leave on the low setting overnight. Drain the stock the next morning and place in pan and reduce it down until it thickens slightly. Leave to cool then freeze until your recipes need some homemade chicken stock.</p>
<p> </p>
